1
00:01:39,253 --> 00:01:41,483
- Package for Robert Garfield.
- Yeah.

2
00:01:41,693 --> 00:01:43,524
- Sign here.
- Thanks.

3
00:02:37,853 --> 00:02:42,608
Whenever it wants, the past can come
kicking the door down.

4
00:02:43,733 --> 00:02:47,089
And you never know
where it's gonna take you.

5
00:02:47,813 --> 00:02:51,169
All you can do is hope
it's a place you wanna go.

6
00:03:03,253 --> 00:03:07,292
You've reached the Garfield family.
Jill and the boys are away.

7
00:03:07,533 --> 00:03:09,967
You can reach them on their cells.

8
00:03:10,173 --> 00:03:14,371
I'll be on the road for a few days.
Be back Tuesday.

9
00:03:19,733 --> 00:03:23,442
On behalf of the president
of the United States...

10
00:03:23,653 --> 00:03:25,723
...I present this flag...

11
00:03:25,933 --> 00:03:28,288
...for the honorable
service rendered...

12
00:03:28,533 --> 00:03:31,969
...by your husband,
Major John Sullivan.

13
00:03:32,173 --> 00:03:35,085
- Hey, Sully!
- Hey!

14
00:03:35,293 --> 00:03:38,763
Bobby, I decided what I wanna be.
A magician.

15
00:03:38,973 --> 00:03:43,171
- I'll pull rabbits out of a hat.
- Rabbits will shit in your hat.

16
00:03:43,373 --> 00:03:46,046
But I'd be a cool bastard.
Admit it.

17
00:03:56,653 --> 00:04:01,408
There's cake at the Veterans Hall.
Of course you're all welcome.

18
00:04:05,293 --> 00:04:07,523
- Mr. Garfield.
- Mr. Oliver.

19
00:04:07,733 --> 00:04:11,521
- Thanks for sending the glove.
- Been Sully's lawyer forever.

20
00:04:11,733 --> 00:04:15,806
Couldn't see why a baseball glove
had to go through probate.

21
00:04:17,053 --> 00:04:21,922
- You and Sully were kids together?
- Yeah, there were three of us.

22
00:04:22,133 --> 00:04:24,886
Me and Sully, and a girl named Carol.

23
00:04:25,093 --> 00:04:26,890
- Carol Gerber?
- That's right.

24
00:04:27,093 --> 00:04:29,049
I'm hoping she'll be here.

25
00:04:31,173 --> 00:04:33,607
You didn't hear about Carol?

26
00:04:35,893 --> 00:04:37,167
No.

27
00:04:40,813 --> 00:04:42,565
I'm afraid she's dead.

28
00:04:44,693 --> 00:04:46,206
I'm so sorry.

29
00:05:27,733 --> 00:05:30,201
This street is where it all happened.

30
00:05:31,093 --> 00:05:32,811
It's not much now.

31
00:05:33,893 --> 00:05:37,124
Why do we always expect home
will stay the same?

32
00:05:37,933 --> 00:05:39,810
Nothing else does.

33
00:05:51,333 --> 00:05:56,123
It's funny how when you're a kid,
a day can last forever.

34
00:05:56,893 --> 00:06:01,330
Now, all these years
seem just like a blink.

35
00:06:44,373 --> 00:06:46,329
Bobby? Bobby-o?

36
00:06:46,733 --> 00:06:48,086
Time to get a wiggle on.

37
00:06:48,293 --> 00:06:50,090
Wake up, Bobby.

38
00:06:52,653 --> 00:06:53,768
Hey, wait for me!

39
00:06:56,733 --> 00:06:58,371
Come on, Johnny.

40
00:07:08,133 --> 00:07:10,886
Happy birthday, Mr. Eleven. Ta-da!

41
00:07:18,893 --> 00:07:22,283
Oh, wow. Library card.

42
00:07:22,533 --> 00:07:26,321
A grownup's library card,
if you please.

43
00:07:28,853 --> 00:07:30,366
Thanks, Mom.

44
00:07:31,213 --> 00:07:32,566
- Is...?
- Don't.

45
00:07:33,173 --> 00:07:37,132
Don't you think I wanted to get you
a bike? I can't afford it.

46
00:07:37,333 --> 00:07:41,451
Know how that makes me feel?
Your father didn't leave us well-off.

47
00:07:41,653 --> 00:07:44,645
He did leave us three months'
unpaid rent...

48
00:07:44,853 --> 00:07:48,482
...a life insurance policy that lapsed
before he died.

49
00:07:48,693 --> 00:07:52,049
He left a rather large stack
of unpaid bills...

50
00:07:52,253 --> 00:07:54,369
...which I managed to take care of.

51
00:07:54,613 --> 00:07:57,207
People understand our situation.

52
00:07:57,413 --> 00:07:59,483
Mr. Biderman is a good example...

53
00:07:59,693 --> 00:08:02,890
...but it has not been easy.
Do you get that?

54
00:08:03,093 --> 00:08:07,530
Your father never met
an inside straight he didn't like.

55
00:08:07,733 --> 00:08:11,009
- What's an inside straight?
- Never you mind, Bobby-o.

56
00:08:11,213 --> 00:08:16,287
Don't let me catch you playing cards.
I've had enough of that.

57
00:08:16,973 --> 00:08:18,372
Come on, then.

58
00:08:20,693 --> 00:08:23,844
That must be the new
upstairs apartment tenant.

59
00:08:24,253 --> 00:08:28,849
I don't trust people who move their
things in paper bags. It's slutty.

60
00:08:29,053 --> 00:08:32,728
- He has suitcases.
- Yes, but they don't match, do they?

61
00:08:32,933 --> 00:08:35,572
Oh, hello, folks. I'm Ted Brautigan.

62
00:08:35,773 --> 00:08:37,570
I'll be living upstairs.

63
00:08:37,773 --> 00:08:40,606
I'm Elizabeth Garfield.
This is my son, Robert.

64
00:08:40,813 --> 00:08:43,373
Nice to meet you, Mr. Brattigan.
Tempus fugit.

65
00:08:43,573 --> 00:08:46,292
It's Brautigan,
but Ted is fine with me.

66
00:08:46,693 --> 00:08:50,288
It's nice to meet you.
I hope you like it here.

67
00:08:50,533 --> 00:08:51,932
Thank you, Robert.

68
00:08:56,373 --> 00:08:57,408
Birthday boy!

69
00:08:58,573 --> 00:09:01,690
Carol, it's hard enough
being friends without that.

70
00:09:01,893 --> 00:09:04,282
You loved it. Here.

71
00:09:04,933 --> 00:09:07,572
- Is this gonna be gushy?
- I don't know.

72
00:09:07,893 --> 00:09:09,565
Better not be.

73
00:09:11,853 --> 00:09:12,808
Whoa.

74
00:09:13,013 --> 00:09:15,243
- Just like it.
- Yeah, that's great.

75
00:09:16,933 --> 00:09:18,651
- Thanks.
- Sure.

76
00:09:21,253 --> 00:09:25,405
- Didn't get the bike, did you?
- No big deal. Mom can't afford it.

77
00:09:25,653 --> 00:09:26,881
She buys new dresses.

78
00:09:27,093 --> 00:09:31,086
She has to look nice for the office.
Are you coming?

79
00:09:32,613 --> 00:09:34,285
- Yeah.
- Come on.

80
00:09:41,173 --> 00:09:43,084
- Hey, Sully!
- Hey!

81
00:09:47,293 --> 00:09:48,487
- Get the bike?
- No.

82
00:09:48,693 --> 00:09:52,402
Well, I got nothing for you.
But happy birthday!

83
00:10:00,093 --> 00:10:02,209
Hang on! Wait for me!

84
00:10:27,853 --> 00:10:31,528
- What's an inside straight?
- Something to do with gambling.

85
00:10:31,733 --> 00:10:36,090
Poker. You draw a middle card.
It's dumb, strictly for suckers.

86
00:10:43,013 --> 00:10:46,005
This neighborhood
is getting terribly run-down.

87
00:10:46,213 --> 00:10:48,249
I think I'll have to move.

88
00:10:54,773 --> 00:10:57,241
- Yeah?
- Is that how we answer the phone?

89
00:10:57,493 --> 00:11:01,771
Hi, Mom. I'm sorry. I was just excited
about dinner and all.

90
00:11:02,853 --> 00:11:07,165
Mr. Biderman has to work late
and needs me to do the same.

91
00:11:07,373 --> 00:11:10,092
So birthday dinner
at the Colony is off.

92
00:11:10,293 --> 00:11:11,248
Okay, Mom.

93
00:11:11,493 --> 00:11:15,122
There are leftovers.
I'll be home to tuck you in.

94
00:11:15,333 --> 00:11:18,166
Oh, make sure to turn
off the gas ring...

95
00:11:18,373 --> 00:11:20,523
...when you're done with the stove.

96
00:11:20,733 --> 00:11:23,531
- I know.
- See you soon.

97
00:11:40,493 --> 00:11:41,846
Evening, Robert.

98
00:11:42,613 --> 00:11:44,365
Or should I say Bobby?

99
00:11:44,613 --> 00:11:47,332
Oh, Mr. Brautigan. Hi.

100
00:11:47,573 --> 00:11:48,767
It's Ted.

101
00:11:50,373 --> 00:11:54,605
Sorry. Ted'll be hard for me,
but I'll try.

102
00:11:55,533 --> 00:11:57,251
You going out later?

103
00:11:59,773 --> 00:12:02,526
I was supposed to have
a birthday dinner.

104
00:12:02,733 --> 00:12:06,487
Mom had to stay at work,
even though she didn't want to.

105
00:12:08,973 --> 00:12:11,043
Are you a rich man then...

106
00:12:12,373 --> 00:12:14,204
...from your birthday gifts?

107
00:12:19,333 --> 00:12:20,971
A library card?

108
00:12:21,773 --> 00:12:24,287
No, an adult library card. Oh, my.

109
00:12:24,893 --> 00:12:27,487
All the master storytellers
waiting for you.

110
00:12:27,693 --> 00:12:31,402
You know why she picked it?
Because it was free.

111
00:12:32,253 --> 00:12:35,768
That doesn't matter.
Don't you give up on this card.

112
00:12:35,973 --> 00:12:38,203
Because books can be solid gold.

113
00:12:38,893 --> 00:12:42,886
The great ones have gotten us
through the nights for centuries.

114
00:12:43,573 --> 00:12:48,044
Give a writer an hour to hook you.
If he can't, find someone else.

115
00:12:48,693 --> 00:12:50,285
Think you can try that?

116
00:12:51,533 --> 00:12:54,001
If I don't have anything else to do.

117
00:12:54,573 --> 00:12:57,167
Fair enough. Don't be afraid.

118
00:12:57,373 --> 00:13:01,332
A Tale of Two Cities ends
with a beheading, great stuff.

119
00:13:01,533 --> 00:13:06,163
Lost Horizon, magic and places
unknown. Can't beat that.

120
00:13:07,933 --> 00:13:12,006
Where'd you live before
you came here, Mr...? Ted?

121
00:13:12,653 --> 00:13:15,372
Some other place
that wasn't as nice as this.

122
00:13:16,533 --> 00:13:17,807
You lived here long?

123
00:13:18,933 --> 00:13:21,970
Yes, sir. Since my dad died.

124
00:13:22,653 --> 00:13:25,725
- When was that sad day?
- When I was 5.

125
00:13:26,733 --> 00:13:28,291
Six years, huh?

126
00:13:29,253 --> 00:13:32,290
You must know everything happening
on this street.

127
00:13:32,533 --> 00:13:37,891
Sure do. Because nothing happens
on this street.

128
00:13:41,013 --> 00:13:44,369
- Six years.
- That's just a blink.

129
00:13:44,613 --> 00:13:46,649
Someday you'll agree.

130
00:13:47,733 --> 00:13:52,124
You know, Ben Jonson called time
"the old bald cheater. "

131
00:13:52,693 --> 00:13:53,728
What?

132
00:13:53,933 --> 00:13:57,687
Ben Jonson called time
"the old bald cheater. "

133
00:13:57,893 --> 00:13:59,372
I like that.

134
00:13:59,613 --> 00:14:03,686
I think I do too. Who's Ben Jonson?

135
00:14:03,893 --> 00:14:06,851
He's an English writer,
dead these many years.

136
00:14:07,413 --> 00:14:09,722
Brilliant, but foolish about money.

137
00:14:09,933 --> 00:14:13,642
And given to flatulence.

138
00:14:13,853 --> 00:14:15,809
What's flatulence?

139
00:14:23,653 --> 00:14:26,121
Yeah, kids always think
farts are funny.

140
00:14:29,613 --> 00:14:33,128
Might have a job for you.
Have to think about it first.

141
00:14:33,973 --> 00:14:35,292
Really?

142
00:14:35,533 --> 00:14:38,889
Yeah. If it works out,
you might get that bike.

143
00:14:42,973 --> 00:14:45,089
How'd you know I wanted a bike?

144
00:14:46,213 --> 00:14:47,965
All kids want bikes.

145
00:15:17,773 --> 00:15:20,810
Hey, Mom. I took another look
at that bike.

146
00:15:21,013 --> 00:15:25,211
It's a Phantom, 26-incher. Real swell.

147
00:15:25,573 --> 00:15:28,690
No, perfect. Perfect is more like it.

148
00:15:28,893 --> 00:15:30,929
Start saving those pennies.

149
00:15:33,053 --> 00:15:35,089
Ted? It's me.

150
00:15:35,693 --> 00:15:36,728
Hi, kid. Come in.

151
00:15:36,933 --> 00:15:39,242
Thanks for making the skyward journey.

152
00:15:39,733 --> 00:15:42,293
An icy root beer awaits you as reward.

153
00:15:42,533 --> 00:15:44,251
The colder, the better.

154
00:15:45,893 --> 00:15:48,930
One feels them first at the back
of one's eyes.

155
00:15:49,893 --> 00:15:51,326
Feels what?

156
00:15:53,653 --> 00:15:56,804
One feels them first
at the back of one's eyes.

157
00:16:02,053 --> 00:16:03,168
Yeah.

158
00:16:05,773 --> 00:16:07,684
Hey, I did like you said.

159
00:16:07,933 --> 00:16:10,128
- What?
- I gave him a couple of hours.

160
00:16:10,333 --> 00:16:13,450
Oh, yeah. Lost Horizon.
What do you think?

161
00:16:13,653 --> 00:16:15,371
Better than the Hardy Boys.

162
00:16:15,613 --> 00:16:17,092
Yeah, sure is.

163
00:16:20,173 --> 00:16:24,724
Tell me, Bobby, how'd you like
to make a dollar a week?

164
00:16:24,933 --> 00:16:26,127
Would I ever?!

165
00:16:26,333 --> 00:16:28,893
Well, my eyes are beginning
to fail me...

166
00:16:29,093 --> 00:16:34,008
...and if you will read me
the Harwich Journal every day...

167
00:16:34,213 --> 00:16:37,205
...headline stuff, sports,
comics, want ads...

168
00:16:37,413 --> 00:16:40,644
...I'll give you said dollar.
What do you say?

169
00:16:43,293 --> 00:16:44,612
What else?

170
00:16:44,933 --> 00:16:46,127
What do you mean?

171
00:16:46,333 --> 00:16:48,801
There's got to be more
to it than that.

172
00:16:50,373 --> 00:16:52,170
Yeah, there is.

173
00:16:53,813 --> 00:16:55,565
So, what's the real job?

174
00:16:56,773 --> 00:16:58,764
Keep your eyes open.

175
00:16:58,973 --> 00:17:01,726
- For what?
- Low men.

176
00:17:03,173 --> 00:17:04,765
That's right, Bobby.

177
00:17:05,973 --> 00:17:09,409
I use the term "low"
in the Dickensian sense...

178
00:17:09,613 --> 00:17:14,323
...meaning dangerous. Men who stop
at nothing to get what they want.

179
00:17:14,733 --> 00:17:17,691
Your real job will simply be...

180
00:17:18,173 --> 00:17:20,050
...to walk around the area...

181
00:17:20,933 --> 00:17:24,084
...and if you see them
or find evidence on them...

182
00:17:24,293 --> 00:17:26,170
...you'll alert me immediately.

183
00:17:26,373 --> 00:17:29,683
Okay. And why are they hot
on your trail?

184
00:17:33,693 --> 00:17:38,005
A certain something I have.
Let's leave it at that.

185
00:17:40,053 --> 00:17:41,691
What do they look like?

186
00:17:44,293 --> 00:17:47,968
Well, they wear dark clothes,
dark hats.

187
00:17:49,413 --> 00:17:51,404
They're kind of anonymous...

188
00:17:51,653 --> 00:17:54,565
...but you can recognize their cars...

189
00:17:54,773 --> 00:17:56,843
...Ioud and flashy.

190
00:17:58,613 --> 00:18:00,888
When they move, they move in packs...

191
00:18:01,093 --> 00:18:03,561
...like animals closing
in on the kill.

192
00:18:07,173 --> 00:18:09,129
And they cast long shadows.

193
00:18:12,333 --> 00:18:13,812
Oh, what a world.

194
00:18:18,133 --> 00:18:21,045
They're not cops, are they?

195
00:18:21,573 --> 00:18:23,325
Or secret agents?

196
00:18:24,853 --> 00:18:29,165
Are you asking me if I'm a bad guy
or a commie spy?

197
00:18:30,293 --> 00:18:32,409
I've scamped my share of fines...

198
00:18:32,653 --> 00:18:35,292
...and if there were library police...

199
00:18:35,533 --> 00:18:38,172
...I'd be one of their
1 0 most wanted.

200
00:18:39,333 --> 00:18:44,043
But I never robbed a bank
or stole a military secret.

201
00:18:44,533 --> 00:18:46,091
So who are they?

202
00:18:47,533 --> 00:18:49,808
They're thugs, relentless...

203
00:18:50,173 --> 00:18:52,528
...when they're after something.

204
00:18:52,733 --> 00:18:55,691
- Like this something you have?
- That's right.

205
00:18:57,533 --> 00:19:01,412
And what they want is me,
back under their control.

206
00:19:01,653 --> 00:19:04,292
Look out. When they're closing in...

207
00:19:04,973 --> 00:19:08,090
...they leave strange signs in code...

208
00:19:08,293 --> 00:19:11,490
...in obvious places
like telephone poles...

209
00:19:11,693 --> 00:19:15,368
...posters and notices
for lost pets and lost dogs.

210
00:19:17,893 --> 00:19:21,408
If I knew what they'd do,
they'd never catch me.

211
00:19:21,653 --> 00:19:25,931
- What do I do if I see them?
- Run and tell me what you've seen.

212
00:19:26,373 --> 00:19:29,604
Remember when I asked if you knew
what was going on around here?

213
00:19:29,813 --> 00:19:34,250
- Sure.
- That's why you're my man, kiddo.

214
00:19:41,533 --> 00:19:44,491
Don't worry,
I won't let the bogeymen get you.

215
00:19:44,693 --> 00:19:48,129
- Bobby?
- She can't know what you're thinking.

216
00:19:48,333 --> 00:19:52,121
You think she can,
and that's a mother's power.

217
00:19:54,333 --> 00:19:55,812
Mrs. Garfield.

218
00:19:59,133 --> 00:20:01,567
Well, it's very cozy in here.

219
00:20:01,773 --> 00:20:04,492
Mom, Ted... I mean, Mr. Brautigan...

220
00:20:04,693 --> 00:20:08,652
...he's gonna pay me a dollar a week
to read him the paper.

221
00:20:09,253 --> 00:20:11,687
Well, that's very generous.

222
00:20:11,893 --> 00:20:15,329
Do you always have boys read to you,
Mr. Brattigan?

223
00:20:15,533 --> 00:20:17,251
It's Brautigan, ma'am.

224
00:20:17,933 --> 00:20:20,606
And, yes, I need someone to do it.

225
00:20:20,813 --> 00:20:23,646
My eyes aren't what they used to be
since I retired.

226
00:20:23,853 --> 00:20:26,242
And what did you do before that?

227
00:20:26,493 --> 00:20:29,485
I worked up north. Various places.

228
00:20:34,693 --> 00:20:38,322
Well, come along, Bobby.
Time and tide wait for no man.

229
00:20:39,693 --> 00:20:41,888
- Bye, Mr. Brautigan.
- Bobby.

230
00:20:51,813 --> 00:20:53,849
Mom, guess what Mr. Brautigan...

231
00:20:58,613 --> 00:21:00,968
- Something doesn't make sense.
- What?

232
00:21:01,173 --> 00:21:04,609
Why would a man his age wanna
spend time with a kid?

233
00:21:04,813 --> 00:21:06,132
I don't know.

234
00:21:06,813 --> 00:21:10,283
I do know that he said
I must be some lucky kid...

235
00:21:10,533 --> 00:21:12,524
...to have a mom who'd let me...

236
00:21:12,733 --> 00:21:16,328
...have a grownup library card
for my birthday.

237
00:21:18,013 --> 00:21:20,208
I don't know. I trust him...

238
00:21:20,413 --> 00:21:23,405
...about as far as I could
sling a piano.

239
00:21:23,653 --> 00:21:28,602
That's right, spoil it for me.
You never want me to get that bike.

240
00:21:28,813 --> 00:21:31,611
I do, and I wish I could've
gotten it for you.

241
00:21:31,813 --> 00:21:34,964
But your father didn't exactly
leave us well-off.

242
00:21:35,853 --> 00:21:37,491
It's only reading.

243
00:21:43,333 --> 00:21:45,847
All right, what's the harm?

244
00:21:46,613 --> 00:21:47,523
Yes, yes, yes!

245
00:21:47,733 --> 00:21:51,521
But only on the porch,
mind, in the fresh air.

246
00:21:51,893 --> 00:21:52,882
Okay.

247
00:22:09,613 --> 00:22:11,729
- Bye, Bobby.
- Bye, Carol.

248
00:22:13,813 --> 00:22:16,043
Sorry I'm late. I forgot the time.

249
00:22:16,253 --> 00:22:17,288
That's all right.

250
00:22:18,053 --> 00:22:21,523
We're all time's captives,
hostages to eternity.

251
00:22:21,733 --> 00:22:22,722
Ben Jonson?

252
00:22:23,893 --> 00:22:25,770
No, Boris Pasternak.

253
00:22:26,053 --> 00:22:29,807
He was a Russian
of no account, I think.

254
00:22:30,693 --> 00:22:33,890
What's going on in the world?
Something scurrilous.

255
00:22:34,093 --> 00:22:36,288
"Vice President Richard M. Nixon...

256
00:22:36,533 --> 00:22:39,570
...after having won
the Republican nomination...

257
00:22:39,773 --> 00:22:43,812
...on the first ballot,
confers with Henry Cabot Lodge..."

258
00:22:44,133 --> 00:22:48,285
- We're going for ice cream.
- Can't. Earning my daily bread.

259
00:22:49,653 --> 00:22:53,089
- Afternoon, Mrs. Gerber. Carol.
- Hi, Ted.

260
00:22:54,933 --> 00:22:59,245
I never, ever saw a girl
as special as Carol Gerber.

261
00:22:59,693 --> 00:23:01,046
There's millions.

262
00:23:01,253 --> 00:23:02,368
Oh, yeah?

263
00:23:03,813 --> 00:23:06,327
- Have you kissed her yet?
- Yuck!

264
00:23:07,013 --> 00:23:09,925
- Well, you will, I promise you.
- Stay away.

265
00:23:11,413 --> 00:23:14,962
You will. It will be the kiss
by which all others...

266
00:23:15,173 --> 00:23:19,371
...in your life will be judged,
and found wanting.

267
00:23:21,373 --> 00:23:22,647
Are you done?

268
00:23:24,693 --> 00:23:28,606
Yeah. Come on, read to me. Go on.

269
00:23:28,813 --> 00:23:32,089
- Come back here and do your job.
- Okay.

270
00:23:34,253 --> 00:23:35,811
But you will kiss her.

271
00:23:40,613 --> 00:23:42,410
Oh, my God!

272
00:23:51,413 --> 00:23:52,528
Nice going.

273
00:23:59,173 --> 00:24:01,971
Get in! Get in, Bobby!

274
00:24:27,413 --> 00:24:30,928
Come on. Come on, Sully.

275
00:24:31,133 --> 00:24:32,486
Sully!

276
00:24:33,413 --> 00:24:38,328
"FBI announces new measures
to combat Red infiltrators. "

277
00:24:40,733 --> 00:24:42,883
- Hey, Bobby.
- Yeah?

278
00:24:43,093 --> 00:24:46,244
Tell me what Dale Arden's wearing
in Flash Gordon.

279
00:24:47,253 --> 00:24:49,483
What is it with you and her?

280
00:24:50,373 --> 00:24:54,525
When I was younger I thought
she was a real hotsie-totsie.

281
00:24:55,973 --> 00:25:00,171
Okay, before comics,
we've got sports, baseball.

282
00:25:00,373 --> 00:25:04,366
"Maury Wills on the way
to break Ty Cobb's record. "

283
00:25:04,613 --> 00:25:05,568
I saw Cobb.

284
00:25:06,533 --> 00:25:10,162
My dad saw Babe Ruth.
He saw him point for the home run.

285
00:25:10,373 --> 00:25:13,524
Against the Cubs.
He told me all about it.

286
00:25:13,733 --> 00:25:16,167
He tell you of Nagurski's
comeback game?

287
00:25:18,253 --> 00:25:21,882
I know he saw it, though.
Were you there?

288
00:25:22,093 --> 00:25:26,371
- Yeah.
- You and Dad were at the same place.

289
00:25:27,293 --> 00:25:29,011
You know about Nagurski?

290
00:25:29,933 --> 00:25:32,322
He was my dad's hero, that's all.

291
00:25:32,813 --> 00:25:36,328
The greatest football player ever.
He came to Chicago...

292
00:25:36,573 --> 00:25:39,610
...played eight years
to make the Bears champions.

293
00:25:39,813 --> 00:25:43,488
Then he retired.
When he was old, six years retired...

294
00:25:43,693 --> 00:25:46,002
...the Bears brought him back.

295
00:25:46,213 --> 00:25:48,966
Last game of the season,
they played...

296
00:25:49,173 --> 00:25:51,368
...the Cardinals, sworn enemies.

297
00:25:52,573 --> 00:25:55,645
The Bears had to beat
the Cardinals to win.

298
00:25:55,933 --> 00:26:00,484
Nagurski wasn't supposed to play.
Third-string fullback.

299
00:26:02,173 --> 00:26:04,562
In the first half
the starter went down.

300
00:26:04,933 --> 00:26:08,289
- The second half there was a pileup.
- Oh, no.

301
00:26:08,533 --> 00:26:11,923
If your dad was here
he'd say he was frightened.

302
00:26:12,133 --> 00:26:16,763
- He was just so scared.
- But why? Nagurski was in the game.

303
00:26:16,973 --> 00:26:19,043
I was scared too. We all were.

304
00:26:19,693 --> 00:26:22,491
We wanted a miracle, you see, Bobby.

305
00:26:23,213 --> 00:26:26,523
We wanted him the way he was,
the old Nagurski.

306
00:26:27,133 --> 00:26:30,045
We wanted him the way he was
in the old days.

307
00:26:30,893 --> 00:26:34,772
Did he do good?
I don't wanna hear this if he didn't.

308
00:26:38,013 --> 00:26:40,368
The quarterback gave him the ball...

309
00:26:40,893 --> 00:26:44,010
...and Nagurski ran slowly
up to the line...

310
00:26:44,533 --> 00:26:46,569
...and the Cardinals crushed him.

311
00:26:46,973 --> 00:26:48,042
But somehow...

312
00:26:50,173 --> 00:26:53,529
...somehow, he gained a few yards.

313
00:26:53,853 --> 00:26:55,332
Next play, the same.

314
00:26:55,573 --> 00:26:59,612
They just kept giving the ball
to the old man...

315
00:27:00,613 --> 00:27:05,733
...and the Bears began to move down
the field, five yards, seven more.

316
00:27:07,253 --> 00:27:10,882
If he could score for us,
we'd be champions again.

317
00:27:13,653 --> 00:27:16,486
Go on, Ted! You can't stop!

318
00:27:22,133 --> 00:27:23,248
Ted!

319
00:27:24,613 --> 00:27:26,922
Come on. I gotta know
what happened.

320
00:27:31,893 --> 00:27:33,212
Come on.

321
00:27:33,413 --> 00:27:35,643
You know what your dad did then?

322
00:27:35,853 --> 00:27:37,844
No, what did my father do?

323
00:27:38,053 --> 00:27:42,604
We were all screaming. We couldn't
believe what was happening.

324
00:27:42,813 --> 00:27:44,883
My God, what was it? Go on.

325
00:27:45,573 --> 00:27:49,964
It was our miracle, you see,
because he was crawling.

326
00:27:50,853 --> 00:27:54,209
Bronko Nagurski was crawling
toward the goal line...

327
00:27:54,413 --> 00:27:57,769
...and they did everything
they could to stop him.

328
00:27:58,493 --> 00:28:00,370
But nothing could stop him.

329
00:28:00,613 --> 00:28:04,891
Yeah, that's right, Bobby.
Not on that day.

330
00:28:06,733 --> 00:28:09,293
Not when your dad and I
saw the miracle...

331
00:28:09,893 --> 00:28:12,248
...when the old man brought us home.

332
00:28:14,733 --> 00:28:18,043
He scored. He scored for us.

333
00:28:20,053 --> 00:28:21,805
We were champions again.

334
00:28:22,653 --> 00:28:24,769
I just knew he would.

335
00:28:28,253 --> 00:28:32,769
Then he was gone again,
back to the North where he came from.

336
00:28:34,573 --> 00:28:36,564
Bronko Nagurski.

337
00:28:37,813 --> 00:28:40,486
Bobby? Bobby-o!

338
00:28:57,599 --> 00:28:59,430
- Ted?
- Yeah?

339
00:29:00,239 --> 00:29:02,912
Well, I know the low men
don't exist...

340
00:29:03,119 --> 00:29:06,191
...but if they started
driving around here...

341
00:29:06,639 --> 00:29:10,348
...and the signs started
appearing on the poles... .

342
00:29:11,119 --> 00:29:13,917
Well, we both know
that couldn't happen.

343
00:29:15,159 --> 00:29:16,797
But if it did...

344
00:29:27,119 --> 00:29:29,269
...would you have to go away?

345
00:29:32,239 --> 00:29:34,912
It wouldn't be safe
for me here.

346
00:29:35,919 --> 00:29:38,308
And wishing cannot make it so.

347
00:29:38,639 --> 00:29:39,958
Bobby!

348
00:29:55,719 --> 00:29:58,711
Bobby? This Ted of yours...

349
00:30:01,039 --> 00:30:03,633
...did he say where he's from?

350
00:30:04,159 --> 00:30:07,037
Someplace not as nice as here,
I think.

351
00:30:09,679 --> 00:30:13,274
Well, that doesn't tell us much,
does it?

352
00:30:14,039 --> 00:30:17,270
- Anything else?
- Nope.

353
00:30:21,239 --> 00:30:22,194
Bobby?

354
00:30:26,679 --> 00:30:30,672
- Does he...?
- What?

355
00:30:35,319 --> 00:30:36,638
Nothing.

356
00:30:38,239 --> 00:30:41,072
You'll tell me if anything
unusual happens?

357
00:30:43,879 --> 00:30:45,232
Hello?

358
00:30:45,439 --> 00:30:46,667
Hi.

359
00:30:50,279 --> 00:30:51,712
You promised.

360
00:30:51,919 --> 00:30:53,591
I really need the...

361
00:30:55,959 --> 00:30:57,278
Who was that?

362
00:30:57,959 --> 00:31:00,427
Nothing, honey.
Just a wrong number.

363
00:31:07,439 --> 00:31:09,077
Son of a bitch!

364
00:31:32,319 --> 00:31:35,516
- I know it's you!
- Your mom says she's almost ready.

365
00:31:35,719 --> 00:31:38,074
- Think Ted would come?
- To the fair?

366
00:31:38,279 --> 00:31:41,237
- Don't you think we should ask?
- I guess.

367
00:31:42,439 --> 00:31:45,112
- You do it. I'll get Sully.
- Okay.

368
00:31:47,119 --> 00:31:51,078
- Do you like being beaten by a girl?
- Hey, no fair.

369
00:32:03,239 --> 00:32:06,197
- Mr. Biderman needs me to go in.
- On Saturday?

370
00:32:06,399 --> 00:32:10,392
- Some people have to work for money.
- Mom, you promised.

371
00:32:10,639 --> 00:32:13,836
These are just Kools.
Read the advertising:

372
00:32:14,039 --> 00:32:18,157
"Kools. They cool the throat. "
They're hardly cigarettes at all.

373
00:32:18,359 --> 00:32:19,678
- Mom?
- What?

374
00:32:19,879 --> 00:32:21,870
Can I have money for the rides?

375
00:32:22,079 --> 00:32:25,708
You never stop, do you?
Aren't you earning money now?

376
00:32:25,919 --> 00:32:26,988
For the bike.

377
00:32:27,199 --> 00:32:32,148
If you want to spend it on rides with
your girlfriend, that's your business.

378
00:32:50,559 --> 00:32:54,393
Ted? It's me.
You wanna come to the fair?

379
00:32:59,839 --> 00:33:00,828
Ted?

380
00:33:19,279 --> 00:33:21,429
Is everything okay?

381
00:33:30,599 --> 00:33:32,351
Ted, wake up.

382
00:33:35,719 --> 00:33:37,437
Ted, you have to help me.

383
00:33:38,119 --> 00:33:40,508
Ted, I don't know what to do.

384
00:33:40,999 --> 00:33:43,229
They draw west now.

385
00:33:44,119 --> 00:33:45,996
Who? Jesus, Ted, please.

386
00:33:46,959 --> 00:33:50,668
They draw west now,
but they may be back.

387
00:33:55,359 --> 00:33:59,034
Ted, please.
You can't die on me.

388
00:34:00,839 --> 00:34:01,874
Please... .

389
00:34:06,199 --> 00:34:07,917
Oh, my God.

390
00:34:08,719 --> 00:34:10,789
What just happened?

391
00:34:14,999 --> 00:34:16,512
I went off again, didn't I?

392
00:34:17,719 --> 00:34:21,189
- You mean, like at the fridge?
- Yeah.

393
00:34:21,399 --> 00:34:23,959
No, way worse.

394
00:34:25,439 --> 00:34:28,192
I thought you were having a fit.

395
00:34:30,039 --> 00:34:31,108
It's all right.

396
00:34:31,679 --> 00:34:34,113
If it happens again,
don't touch me.

397
00:34:34,839 --> 00:34:37,307
Nobody should touch me,
that's all.

398
00:34:37,799 --> 00:34:39,357
Sorry.

399
00:34:41,799 --> 00:34:44,916
- Is it safe to leave you alone?
- Yeah.

400
00:34:48,159 --> 00:34:49,672
It's okay.

401
00:34:54,279 --> 00:34:55,428
Okay.

402
00:35:00,159 --> 00:35:02,593
Mrs. Gerber's taking us to the fair.

403
00:35:02,799 --> 00:35:05,996
Carol and I thought you
might like to come.

404
00:35:06,199 --> 00:35:11,068
Thank you, Bobby,
but I think just now, it's not wise.

405
00:35:12,079 --> 00:35:14,070
- Okay.
- Okay.

406
00:35:21,359 --> 00:35:23,589
The cigarettes are on the table.

407
00:35:25,839 --> 00:35:27,636
Thanks, kiddo.

408
00:35:28,719 --> 00:35:30,072
What's so funny?

409
00:35:30,719 --> 00:35:35,315
You run along now. Enjoy yourself.
Don't fall out of anything.

410
00:35:56,399 --> 00:35:58,355
Yes! That one.

411
00:36:17,639 --> 00:36:18,594
No!

412
00:36:19,399 --> 00:36:21,196
Yes!

413
00:36:23,519 --> 00:36:25,157
What are you gonna name it?

414
00:36:25,359 --> 00:36:30,353
All right. Step right up!
Hey, who feels lucky?

415
00:36:30,599 --> 00:36:32,829
Find the queen of hearts and win.

416
00:36:33,039 --> 00:36:35,678
- It already happened!
- Just once.

417
00:36:35,879 --> 00:36:37,551
Easy peas-y Japanese-y.

418
00:36:37,759 --> 00:36:40,671
Just find the queen of hearts.

419
00:36:40,999 --> 00:36:44,912
- Put down your bet. I'll do it again.
- A quarter.

420
00:36:45,119 --> 00:36:46,108
See, a jack.

421
00:36:46,599 --> 00:36:51,593
We got the king and we got the queen.
Tell me where she lands.

422
00:36:57,119 --> 00:36:59,679
- Fortune awaits you.
- That one there.

423
00:37:00,559 --> 00:37:01,833
- Yes!
- Genius.

424
00:37:02,039 --> 00:37:05,634
- I told you!
- Wait. Double and add a half-dollar.

425
00:37:05,839 --> 00:37:06,908
Okay.

426
00:37:17,399 --> 00:37:18,798
That one there.

427
00:37:19,999 --> 00:37:22,832
- Heartbreak.
- That's enough. I have to stop.

428
00:37:23,039 --> 00:37:26,429
- I can spot his moves.
- I better give up then.

429
00:37:26,679 --> 00:37:29,273
- Just a quarter.
- One, okay.

430
00:37:30,959 --> 00:37:35,828
Up and down, all around.
In and out, all about.

431
00:37:36,039 --> 00:37:37,358
Now they're back...

432
00:37:37,599 --> 00:37:40,238
...side by side.

433
00:37:40,439 --> 00:37:43,397
Tell me, mister.
Where's she hide?

434
00:37:44,399 --> 00:37:45,673
It's on the right.

435
00:37:46,079 --> 00:37:49,116
No. It's the one on the left.
Right there.

436
00:37:52,239 --> 00:37:54,150
- Okay, enough.
- There she is.

437
00:37:54,359 --> 00:37:56,589
- Bobby was right.
- A prodigy, huh?

438
00:37:56,799 --> 00:38:01,077
- Why don't you win it back?
- I could, but I can't play for money.

439
00:38:01,279 --> 00:38:02,234
A boast-y boy.

440
00:38:02,439 --> 00:38:05,237
Says he can win,
but afraid to back it up.

441
00:38:05,599 --> 00:38:09,069
I could have my money back.
Come on. Beat him.

442
00:38:09,279 --> 00:38:13,431
- I can't. Your mother won't be happy.
- Beat him, come on.

443
00:38:13,639 --> 00:38:16,790
My mom's never happy.
It's all I got.

444
00:38:16,999 --> 00:38:21,948
This is the move that stunned
the sheik of Araby. Behold.

445
00:38:31,359 --> 00:38:33,634
This one here, in the middle.

446
00:38:38,559 --> 00:38:40,356
- All right!
- That's it!

447
00:38:42,879 --> 00:38:44,028
A lucky guess.

448
00:38:44,239 --> 00:38:47,948
Double your bet.
That way we all go home happy.

449
00:38:48,919 --> 00:38:50,318
Fine.

450
00:38:56,999 --> 00:38:59,593
This one is five years of my life.

451
00:39:38,799 --> 00:39:40,391
This one here.

452
00:39:42,839 --> 00:39:44,955
Nobody ever beat that shuffle.

453
00:39:47,599 --> 00:39:50,238
Well, mister,
is it or isn't it?

454
00:39:53,359 --> 00:39:55,998
- Yes, that's it! Okay.
- All right!

455
00:39:56,199 --> 00:39:59,635
- It was a fluke.
- You bet it was a fluke.

456
00:40:03,199 --> 00:40:04,473
Now beat it, kid.

457
00:40:04,679 --> 00:40:08,274
Okay, gang, let's go. That's enough.
Come on, Bobby.

458
00:40:10,879 --> 00:40:13,029
Step right up!
We had a winner!

459
00:40:13,239 --> 00:40:15,912
It's easy as can be.
Easy peas-y Japanese-y!

460
00:40:24,559 --> 00:40:25,514
Yes, yes.

461
00:40:36,119 --> 00:40:37,552
Don't be afraid.

462
00:40:37,759 --> 00:40:41,991
When we swung out, I was afraid
we would fall to our doom.

463
00:40:42,959 --> 00:40:45,268
We're as safe as can be.

464
00:40:48,919 --> 00:40:51,387
What do you think you're doing?

465
00:40:51,639 --> 00:40:54,278
Well, I thought you wanted me to.

466
00:40:55,999 --> 00:40:58,911
I just wasn't ready, that's all.

467
00:40:59,519 --> 00:41:00,872
Okay.

468
00:41:03,959 --> 00:41:07,713
- Bobby, do it again.
- I better not. You'll tell.

469
00:41:08,159 --> 00:41:11,868
No, it'll be our secret.
Hurry, before we go down.

470
00:41:15,759 --> 00:41:18,876
Bobby, I'm dying here.

471
00:41:38,319 --> 00:41:41,231
Thank you.
That was the nicest thing.

472
00:41:42,519 --> 00:41:46,194
It'll be the kiss by which
all others will be judged.

473
00:41:46,399 --> 00:41:47,593
What?

474
00:41:48,079 --> 00:41:50,798
Sounded better when Ted said it.

475
00:42:10,399 --> 00:42:14,438
You knew, didn't you, where
the queen of hearts was?

476
00:42:15,719 --> 00:42:19,348
I could tell what was
going on in his head.

477
00:42:19,559 --> 00:42:23,393
Every thought he had, I knew,
and he couldn't fool me.

478
00:42:23,679 --> 00:42:26,591
Can you tell what's in Sully's head?

479
00:42:27,919 --> 00:42:29,716
Sully's head's always empty.

480
00:42:29,919 --> 00:42:33,912
Oh, yeah? Maybe I'm thinking
of getting a new glove.

481
00:42:34,119 --> 00:42:37,270
You are?
Well, what about that one?

482
00:42:38,439 --> 00:42:41,158
- Want it?
- Are you kidding? I love it!

483
00:42:41,439 --> 00:42:44,112
- Then, Bobby, it's yours.
- It is?

484
00:42:44,319 --> 00:42:46,435
I'll leave it to you in my will.

485
00:42:48,159 --> 00:42:51,993
- Sully, you just love doing that!
- I got you again.

486
00:42:54,079 --> 00:42:56,468
You know, when you're young...

487
00:42:56,679 --> 00:42:59,432
...you have moments
of such happiness...

488
00:42:59,679 --> 00:43:03,308
...you think you're living
in someplace magical...

489
00:43:04,159 --> 00:43:06,070
...like Atlantis must have been.

490
00:43:06,279 --> 00:43:10,750
- Carol, I owe you $ 75. It's your turn.
- Okay.

491
00:43:12,719 --> 00:43:15,153
- Here, give me $25 back.
- Twenty-five.

492
00:43:15,359 --> 00:43:17,077
- Here. $22.
- Okay. Wait, no!

493
00:43:17,279 --> 00:43:21,636
- No! Hold on.
